"{\n  \"Infant\": {\n    \"body\": \"The first three years of life are a critical developmental window for humans, encompassing microbiome seeding, immune system maturation, and metabolic priming. Our suite of microbiome-centric solutions seeds the appropriate bacteria at the optimal time to establish a strong symbiotic host-microbiome relationship from the beginning of life.\",\n    \"scientists\": [\n      \"ERAN SEGAL PH.D, THE WEIZMANN INSTITUTE OF SCIENCE\",\n      \"CEZMI AKDIS, MD, UNIVERSITY OF ZURICH (SIAF)\",\n      \"JACQUES RAVEL, PHD, UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND SCHOOL OF MEDICINE\"\n    ],\n    \"apps\": [\n      \"GASTROINTESTINAL HEALTH\",\n      \"DERMATOLOGICAL HEALTH\"\n    ],\n    \"img\": \"https://images.ctfassets.net/oq6r31hkrb9r/7i0WHTLu6nX2PsIxmizB9j/5ebac72ce2590584de7424a0ab10c7bf/2018_SEED_2682_3.jpg\"\n  },\n  \"Pediatric\": {\n    \"body\": \"Following the transition to solid foods, the microbiome exerts influence as a metabolic organ regulating the gastrointestinal, metabolic, and neurocognitive systems as it transitions into a steady-state. Our solutions are designed to protect the microbiome from early disruptions due to modern living.\",\n    \"scientists\": [\n      \"JAMES VERSALOVIC, MD, PHD, BAYLOR COLLEGE OF MEDICINE\",\n      \"ALESSIO FASANO, MD, HARVARD MEDICAL SCHOOL\",\n      \"KARI NADEAU, MD, PHD, HARVARD MEDICAL SCHOOL\",\n      \"CEZMI AKDIS, MD, UNIVERSITY OF ZURICH\"\n    ],\n    \"apps\": [\n      \"GASTROINTESTINAL HEALTH\",\n      \"METABOLIC HEALTH\",\n      \"DERMATOLOGICAL HEALTH\"\n    ],\n    \"img\": \"https://images.ctfassets.net/oq6r31hkrb9r/2ubbxTzV1q0SmHCmRvJr4w/7594ecc43fa396e1a7812dda275e7c0f/Daniel-Faro__DTS_Parenthood_035_2.jpg\"\n  },\n  \"Adult\": {\n    \"body\": \"The steady-state adult microbiome is constantly challenged by dietary, lifestyle, pharmaceutical and environmental factors. These cumulative effects interfere with metabolic, neurological, and skin function, representing a key window of intervention. Our solutions focus on various states of dysbiosis that emerge from external factors.\",\n    \"scientists\": [\n      \"ERAN SEGAL PH.D, THE WEIZMANN INSTITUTE OF SCIENCE\",\n      \"CEZMI AKDIS, MD, UNIVERSITY OF ZURICH (SIAF)\",\n      \"JACQUES RAVEL, PHD, UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND SCHOOL OF MEDICINE\",\n      \"SARKIS MAZMANIAN, PHD, CALTECH\"\n    ],\n    \"apps\": [\n      \"GASTROINTESTINAL HEALTH\",\n      \"METABOLIC HEALTH\",\n      \"NEUROCOGNITIVE HEALTH\",\n      \"DERMATOLOGICAL HEALTH\"\n    ],\n    \"img\": \"https://images.ctfassets.net/oq6r31hkrb9r/6k9dEvwEOB8Trj5IvTZtpN/575892a0a407d7d7f048949af143b9b5/nsey-benajah-P-0xj_CW86Y-unsplash_2.jpg\"\n  },\n  \"Aging\": {\n    \"body\": \"Biological and chronological age differ substantially and the microbiome is a key predictor of healthy aging across many organ systems of the body. In addition, keystone species begin to degrade and sex-specific differences emerge.  This is a nuanced opportunity to re-seed the aging microbiome and reestablish keystone communities associated with health earlier in life.\",\n    \"scientists\": [\n      \"ERAN SEGAL PH.D, THE WEIZMANN INSTITUTE OF SCIENCE\",\n      \"JACQUES RAVEL, PHD, UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND SCHOOL OF MEDICINE\",\n      \"GEORGE CHURCH, PHD, HARVARD MEDICAL SCHOOL\"\n    ],\n    \"apps\": [\n      \"GASTROINTESTINAL HEALTH\",\n      \"METABOLIC HEALTH\",\n      \"NEUROCOGNITIVE HEALTH\",\n      \"DERMATOLOGICAL HEALTH\"\n    ],\n    \"img\": \"https://images.ctfassets.net/oq6r31hkrb9r/yZlNZfpOp9sQk1RuxNR0S/beae1e0f6d2fd11723ea1dad5b4997cd/AdobeStock_87858298.jpeg\"\n  }\n}"